Rating: 3
This is a good basic recipe for lasagna. The noodle layering technique ensures that it won't fall apart at serving time, and the use of sauce rather than oil under the first layer of noodles minimizes noodle slippage when adding the ricotta-spinach mixture. I've made this a few times, and I'd suggest some minor changes. First, I omit the carrots from the sauce. They add an unnecessary foreign flavor to the familiar one of the sauce. Also, the brown sugar is not a necessity. The tomatoes and paste bring enough sweetness to the sauce on their own. As for the ricotta-spinach mixture, I suggest adding one (or more, depending on your preference) clove of garlic that is either put throw a garlic press or mashed in a mortar and pestle. Ricotta and spinach are relatively bland, and the parmesan adds only a minimal amount of flavor.

Rating: 4
I made this for an oldtimer's reunion of 20 people and it was a hit. The tomato sauce needed more substance and kick so I added sliced and steamed zucchini and Cajun Tabasco Peppers with the seeds removed, and tons of freshly ground cummin to that. The ricotta spinach part needed more creaminess and flavor so I made a thick bechamel sauce with a whole freshly ground nutmeg (or almost all so I wouldn't destroy my manicure in the grating) and added that to the spinach part. The balance between the spicy, chunky red sauce and creamy nutmegy white sauce was divine. You can cut the calories by substituting turkey sausage and minced chicken for the meat and non-fat cottage cheese for the ricotta. If the parmesan is salty enough you can use less of that. I also used a jar of Ragu chunky vegetable with garlic and onion instead of the crushed tomatoes. It made the red sauce very substantive. A great company dish served with a mixed salad with balsamic vinegar and oil and crunchy fresh herb bread.(I used all fresh herbs on top of Girard's Lite Champaign Dressing.) The whole menue was a symphony of spicey, creamy, chunky, crisp, crunchy,sweet, hot, and cold.

